To update your background and switch from online URLs to local images, you'll need to modify the body and .home-bg sections of your CSS.

 1. Changing the Background Color
Currently, your body uses a linear-gradient. To change it to a solid color or a different gradient, update the background property:

 * **For a solid color:**
   ```css
   body {
       background: #2c3e50; /* Replace with your Hex or RGB code */
       background-attachment: fixed;
       min-height: 100vh;
       font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
       color: white;
   }
   
   ```

 * **For a different gradient:** Change the Hex codes in linear-gradient(135deg, #color1 0%, #color2 100%).


2. Linking Downloaded (Local) Images
To use images you've downloaded, follow these steps:
step A: Organize your Folders
Create a folder named images in the same directory as your index.html and style.css. Move your downloaded images into that folder.
Step B: Update the CSS Path
In your CSS, replace the Unsplash URL with the relative path to your file (e.g., images/my-background.jpg).

Update for .home-bg:
```css
.home-bg {
    min-height: 100vh; 
    /* Keep the overlay gradient, just change the URL at the end */
    background: linear-gradient(rgba(102, 126, 234, 0.4), rgba(118, 75, 162, 0.6)), 
                url('images/your-local-image.jpg'); 
    background-size: cover;
    background-position: center;
    background-repeat: no-repeat;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
}



#### Step C: Update HTML Images
For images like the one using .hero-img or .about-me-photo, you need to update the src attribute in your **HTML** files (like index.html or rental.html):


```html
<img src="images/profile-picture.jpg" class="about-me-photo" alt="Profile Photo">

```

### Quick Tips for Local Images:
 * **File Extensions:** Ensure the extension in your code matches the file exactly (e.g., .jpg is different from .jpeg or .png).
 * **No Spaces:** Avoid using spaces in your image filenames (use hero_bg.jpg instead of hero bg.jpg).
 * **Case Sensitivity:** On many hosting platforms, Image.jpg and image.jpg are considered different files. It is best practice to keep everything lowercase.
